TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Characterization of M/G/1 Queues with Renewal Departure Processes
AU  - Disney, Ralph L.
AU  - Farrell, Robert L.
AU  - De Morais, Paulo Renato
Y1  - 1973/07/01
PY  - 1973
DA  - 1973/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.19.11.1222
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.19.11.1222
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1222
EP  - 1228
VL  - 19
IS  - 11
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Burke [Burke, P. J. 1956. The output of a queueing system. Oper. Res. 4 699?704.] showed that the departure process from an M/M/1 queue with infinite capacity was in fact a Poisson process. Using methods from semi-Markov process theory, this paper extends this result by determining that the departure process from an M/G/1 queue is a renewal process if and only if the queue is in steady state and one of the following four conditions holds: (1) the queue is the null queue?the service times are all 0; (2) the queue has capacity (excluding the server) 0; (3) the queue has capacity 1 and the service times are constant (deterministic); or (4) the queue has infinite capacity and the service times are negatively exponentially distributed (M/M/1/∞ queue).
AB  - Burke [Burke, P. J. 1956. The output of a queueing system. Oper. Res. 4 699?704.] showed that the departure process from an M/M/1 queue with infinite capacity was in fact a Poisson process. Using methods from semi-Markov process theory, this paper extends this result by determining that the departure process from an M/G/1 queue is a renewal process if and only if the queue is in steady state and one of the following four conditions holds: (1) the queue is the null queue?the service times are all 0; (2) the queue has capacity (excluding the server) 0; (3) the queue has capacity 1 and the service times are constant (deterministic); or (4) the queue has infinite capacity and the service times are negatively exponentially distributed (M/M/1/∞ queue).
